{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Open a web browser and go to `https://git-scm.com/downloads`. The page lists official Git downloads for Windows, macOS, and Linux.",
      "title": "Open Git Downloads"
    },
    {
      "text": "Select your computer’s operating system on the downloads page. Choose **Windows**, **macOS**, or **Linux** to open the matching download page.",
      "title": "Choose Your Operating System"
    },
    {
      "text": "Download the installer shown for your operating system. The file should appear in your browser’s Downloads folder or download list.",
      "title": "Download Git"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open the downloaded installer. On Windows, open the `.exe` file; on macOS, open the `.dmg` or package; on Linux, follow the displayed instructions for your distribution.",
      "title": "Launch the Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Follow the installer prompts and accept the default options. On Windows and macOS, continue until the installer reports that Git has finished installing.",
      "title": "Complete Installation"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open a command-line application: Git Bash or PowerShell on Windows, Terminal on macOS, or Terminal on Linux. A command prompt should appear.",
      "title": "Open a Terminal"
    },
    {
      "text": "Type `git --version` and press Enter. Git should print a version such as `git version 2.45.0`; this confirms the command is available.",
      "title": "Check the Git Version"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the command is not found, close and reopen the terminal, then run `git --version` again. If it still fails, reinstall Git and ensure the installer adds Git to your command path.",
      "title": "Resolve Verification Issues"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Park on Firm, Level Ground",
      "title": "Park Safely"
    },
    {
      "text": "Move the vehicle onto firm, level ground away from traffic. Turn on the hazard lights, set the parking brake, and shift into Park or first gear. Confirm the vehicle is stable before continuing.",
      "title": "Park Safely"
    },
    {
      "text": "Read your owner’s manual to find the vehicle’s approved jacking point and the location of the spare-tire tools. Use only the jacking point listed for the flat tire.",
      "title": "Check the Manual"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place wheel chocks snugly against the tire opposite the flat tire. Use rocks or blocks only if proper chocks are unavailable. Confirm the blocked wheel cannot roll.",
      "title": "Block a Wheel"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove the jack, lug wrench, and any locking-lug key from the vehicle. Keep them beside the flat tire so you can reach them without moving the vehicle.",
      "title": "Gather the Tools"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pry off the wheel cover if it hides the lug nuts. Use the flat end of the lug wrench or the tool supplied with the vehicle. The lug nuts should now be fully visible.",
      "title": "Expose the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Fit the lug wrench over one lug nut and turn it counterclockwise. Break the nut loose without removing it. Repeat for every lug nut while the tire remains on the ground.",
      "title": "Loosen the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Position the jack under the approved jacking point shown in the manual. Make sure the jack’s base sits flat and fully contacts the vehicle’s jacking point.",
      "title": "Position the Jack"
    },
    {
      "text": "Raise the vehicle slowly with the jack handle. Stop when the flat tire is about 2 inches (5 cm) above the ground, and never place any part of your body underneath it.",
      "title": "Lift the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove each loosened lug nut by turning it counterclockwise by hand or with the wrench. Place the nuts together where they cannot roll away.",
      "title": "Remove the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pull the flat tire straight toward you using both hands. If it sticks, keep the vehicle supported and tap the tire’s sidewall gently; never crawl under the vehicle.",
      "title": "Pull Off the Tire"
    },
    {
      "text": "Set the removed tire flat on the ground beside the vehicle. Confirm the wheel is fully off the hub and the vehicle remains stable on the jack.",
      "title": "Secure the Flat Tire"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Place your French press, a scale, a timer, a spoon, and two cups on a stable surface. Confirm the press is clean and the plunger moves freely.",
      "title": "Set Up Your Equipment"
    },
    {
      "text": "Measure 30 grams of medium-coarse coffee grounds into a dry bowl or directly into the press. The grounds should resemble coarse sea salt.",
      "title": "Measure the Grounds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Heat 500 grams of water to about 200°F (93°C). If you cannot set the temperature, stop heating just before the water reaches a full boil.",
      "title": "Heat the Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Add the measured coffee grounds to the bottom of the French press. Tap the press gently so the grounds form an even layer.",
      "title": "Add the Grounds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the hot water into the press until the scale reads 500 grams. Make sure all the grounds are wet and floating near the surface.",
      "title": "Pour in the Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Stir the mixture gently once with a spoon. The grounds should be evenly saturated, with no dry patches visible.",
      "title": "Stir the Coffee"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the lid on the press with the plunger pulled fully up. The lid should sit flat and keep heat from escaping.",
      "title": "Place the Lid"
    },
    {
      "text": "Set a timer for 4 minutes. The timer should begin immediately after the lid is in place.",
      "title": "Start the Timer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Wait until the 4-minute timer ends. A dark layer of grounds should settle near the top and the coffee should smell fragrant.",
      "title": "Steep for Four Minutes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the plunger down slowly and steadily until it reaches the bottom. Stop if you feel strong resistance, then press more gently.",
      "title": "Plunge the Coffee"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the brewed coffee into your cups immediately. Empty the press so the coffee does not continue steeping and become bitter.",
      "title": "Pour and Serve"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Gather a garden fork or spade, rake, gloves, finished compost, and a bucket or wheelbarrow. Keep the bed accessible and free of planted crops.",
      "title": "Gather Your Tools"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove weeds, rocks, and plant debris from the garden bed by hand. The surface should be clear before you work the soil.",
      "title": "Clear the Bed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check the soil moisture by squeezing a handful. It should crumble when pressed; if it forms a sticky ball, wait until it dries slightly.",
      "title": "Check Soil Moisture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Break up the top 10–12 inches of soil with a garden fork or spade. Lift and turn the soil without pulverizing it.",
      "title": "Loosen the Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Spread a 2–3-inch layer of finished compost evenly across the loosened bed. The compost should cover the surface without large piles.",
      "title": "Add Finished Compost"
    },
    {
      "text": "Mix the compost into the top 6–8 inches of soil with your fork or spade. The soil should look evenly blended, with no thick compost layer remaining.",
      "title": "Blend the Compost"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rake the bed level and break apart remaining clumps larger than a golf ball. The finished surface should be loose, even, and free of hollows.",
      "title": "Condition the Surface"
    },
    {
      "text": "Water the prepared bed slowly until the top 6 inches feel evenly moist. Stop when water begins to pool, and let excess water drain away.",
      "title": "Moisten the Bed"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Gather the pattern, washed fabric, measuring tape, fabric marker, fabric scissors, and pins. Place everything on a large, flat surface with good lighting.",
      "title": "Gather Your Supplies"
    },
    {
      "text": "Spread the fabric flat with the wrong side facing up. Smooth out wrinkles so the edges and grain lie straight.",
      "title": "Lay Out the Fabric"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the pattern pieces on the fabric according to their grainline arrows and any fold markings. Keep the layout within the available fabric.",
      "title": "Position the Pattern"
    },
    {
      "text": "Measure the distance from each pattern edge to the fabric edge. Confirm the pattern matches the measurements and layout shown in its instructions.",
      "title": "Check the Pattern Layout"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pin each pattern piece to the fabric around its edges. Place pins perpendicular to the cutting line so they hold the piece securely.",
      "title": "Pin the Pattern"
    },
    {
      "text": "Trace around each pinned pattern piece with a fabric marker if the pattern requires marked cutting lines. Follow the pattern’s seam-allowance line exactly.",
      "title": "Mark the Cutting Lines"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cut around the first pattern piece with fabric scissors. Keep the scissor blades beside the marked line and use long, steady cuts.",
      "title": "Cut the First Piece"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cut around each remaining pattern piece using the same marked lines. Remove pins as you approach them, and keep the fabric flat while cutting.",
      "title": "Cut the Remaining Pieces"
    },
    {
      "text": "Separate the cut pieces from the extra fabric. You should have every pillowcase piece listed on the pattern, with clean edges and no uncut sections.",
      "title": "Separate the Pieces"
    },
    {
      "text": "Compare each cut piece with its pattern piece. Confirm the shape, size, grainline direction, and any notches or markings match before sewing.",
      "title": "Verify the Cut Pieces"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Set your guitar in playing position with the thickest string nearest the ceiling. Keep your tuning pegs accessible and your picking hand free. You should be able to pluck each string separately.",
      "title": "Position Your Guitar"
    },
    {
      "text": "Choose a chromatic tuner, clip-on tuner, or reference-pitch source. If using a tuner, turn it on; if using a reference, open the standard-tuning pitches E, A, D, G, B, and E.",
      "title": "Choose a Tuning Method"
    },
    {
      "text": "Identify the thickest string as the 6th string. Its standard pitch is low E, written `E`. You should see or hear the target pitch before adjusting the string.",
      "title": "Find the Low E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 6th string once and watch the tuner, or compare it with the low E reference pitch. Let the string ring clearly so the pitch reading can settle.",
      "title": "Check the Low E"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the 6th-string tuning peg in small movements until the tuner centers on `E`, or the string matches the low E reference. The pitch should remain steady after you pluck again.",
      "title": "Tune the Low E"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 5th string and compare it with the `A` target on your tuner or reference source. This is the second-thickest string, and its reading should settle near A.",
      "title": "Check the A String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the 5th-string tuning peg in small movements until the tuner centers on `A`, or the string matches the A reference. Pluck again to confirm the pitch stays on target.",
      "title": "Tune the A String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 4th string and compare it with the `D` target. This is the third-thickest string, and the tuner should identify its pitch as D when it is correctly tuned.",
      "title": "Check the D String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the 4th-string tuning peg in small movements until the tuner centers on `D`, or the string matches the D reference. Pluck again to verify the pitch.",
      "title": "Tune the D String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 3rd string and compare it with the `G` target. The tuner should show G, or the string should match the G reference pitch.",
      "title": "Check the G String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the 3rd-string tuning peg in small movements until the tuner centers on `G`, or the string matches the G reference. Pluck again to confirm it is steady.",
      "title": "Tune the G String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 2nd string and compare it with the `B` target. The tuner should show B, or the string should match the B reference pitch.",
      "title": "Check the B String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the 2nd-string tuning peg in small movements until the tuner centers on `B`, or the string matches the B reference. Pluck again to verify the pitch.",
      "title": "Tune the B String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thinnest string and compare it with the high `E` target. Make sure you are tuning the 1st string, not the thicker 2nd string.",
      "title": "Check the High E"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the 1st-string tuning peg in small movements until the tuner centers on `E`, or the string matches the high E reference. Pluck again to confirm the pitch.",
      "title": "Tune the High E"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck all six strings one at a time from thickest to thinnest. The tuner should show `E A D G B E` in order, or each string should match its reference pitch.",
      "title": "Verify Standard Tuning"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Mount your camera and attach the lens you will use. Turn the camera on and select a mode that lets you change ISO, aperture, and shutter speed, such as Manual (M).",
      "title": "Prepare the Camera"
    },
    {
      "text": "Frame your scene through the viewfinder or screen. Keep the subject and lighting visible so you can judge the exposure while adjusting settings.",
      "title": "Frame the Scene"
    },
    {
      "text": "Set the aperture for the desired depth of field. Use a smaller f-number, such as f/2.8, for more background blur; use a larger f-number, such as f/11, for more of the scene in focus.",
      "title": "Set the Aperture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Set the shutter speed for the desired motion effect. Choose a faster speed, such as 1/500 s, to freeze motion; choose a slower speed, such as 1/30 s, for more motion blur.",
      "title": "Set the Shutter Speed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Set the ISO to the lowest value that provides enough brightness, starting around ISO 100 or 200 in bright light. Increase it only when the aperture and shutter speed cannot provide enough exposure.",
      "title": "Set the ISO"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check the exposure meter in the viewfinder or screen. Adjust the settings until the indicator reaches 0 or the camera reports a balanced exposure; the exact display varies by model.",
      "title": "Check the Exposure Meter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Capture a test photo by pressing the shutter button fully. Review the image and histogram if available; highlights should not be broadly clipped and important shadows should retain detail.",
      "title": "Take a Test Photo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Correct the exposure if needed. Darken a bright image by lowering ISO, closing the aperture, or using a faster shutter speed; brighten a dark image by reversing one of those adjustments.",
      "title": "Refine the Exposure"
    },
    {
      "text": "Take the final photo after the preview looks properly exposed and the subject's details are visible. Your camera should record an image with balanced highlights, shadows, and overall brightness.",
      "title": "Capture the Final Photo"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Stand with your feet about shoulder-width apart. Turn your toes slightly outward, keeping both feet fully planted. Your stance is ready when you feel balanced without shifting your weight.",
      "title": "Set Your Stance"
    },
    {
      "text": "Straighten your spine and lift your chest without arching your lower back. Keep your head neutral and look forward at a fixed point. Your ears should stay over your shoulders.",
      "title": "Align Your Upper Body"
    },
    {
      "text": "Brace your core as if preparing for a gentle punch. Keep this tension while breathing normally. Your torso should feel supported, not rigid or strained.",
      "title": "Brace Your Core"
    },
    {
      "text": "Bend your knees and push your hips backward to begin the squat. Keep your heels on the floor. Your hips and knees should start moving together.",
      "title": "Begin the Descent"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lower your body while keeping your knees in line with your toes. Do not let your knees collapse inward. Check that they track over the middle of your feet.",
      "title": "Track Your Knees"
    },
    {
      "text": "Continue lowering until your thighs are about parallel to the floor, or as far as you can go while keeping your heels down and spine neutral. Stop if your form changes.",
      "title": "Reach Your Depth"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press through your whole foot to stand up. Straighten your hips and knees without locking your knees forcefully. You should return to your original balanced stance.",
      "title": "Stand Up Smoothly"
    },
    {
      "text": "Complete five slow bodyweight squats, using the same positioning on every repetition. Move at a controlled pace and stop if you feel sharp pain, dizziness, or loss of balance.",
      "title": "Practice Five Repetitions"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check your final position in a mirror or video. Confirm that your heels stayed down, knees tracked over your toes, and back remained neutral throughout the movement.",
      "title": "Verify Your Form"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Separe 500 g de farinha de trigo, 10 g de fermento biológico seco, 300 ml de água morna, 1 colher de sopa de açúcar, 1 colher de chá de sal e 2 colheres de sopa de óleo. Deixe tudo ao alcance.",
      "title": "Separe os ingredientes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloque a água morna em uma tigela e adicione o fermento e o açúcar. Misture até incorporar. A água deve estar morna, não quente, para não prejudicar o fermento.",
      "title": "Misture o fermento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aguarde de 5 a 10 minutos. Uma espuma ou bolhas devem aparecer na superfície, indicando que o fermento foi ativado.",
      "title": "Aguarde a ativação"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloque a farinha e o sal em uma tigela grande. Misture os dois ingredientes secos até o sal ficar distribuído.",
      "title": "Misture os ingredientes secos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Despeje a mistura de fermento e o óleo sobre a farinha. Os líquidos devem cobrir parte da farinha.",
      "title": "Adicione os líquidos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Misture tudo com uma colher ou com as mãos até formar uma massa úmida e sem farinha solta. Se ficar muito pegajosa, acrescente farinha aos poucos.",
      "title": "Forme a massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Sove a massa sobre uma superfície enfarinhada por 8 a 10 minutos, empurrando-a com a base da mão e dobrando-a repetidamente. Ela deve ficar lisa e elástica.",
      "title": "Sove a massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Faça uma bola com a massa e pressione-a levemente com um dedo. Se ela voltar à forma e estiver macia, a massa está pronta para a próxima etapa.",
      "title": "Verifique a massa"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Reúne una llave ajustable, destornilladores, pinzas, paño, repuesto compatible y cinta de plomería. Ten una cubeta cerca para recoger el agua.",
      "title": "Reúne las herramientas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca la cubeta debajo del grifo y el paño sobre el desagüe. Así evitarás perder tornillos y bloquearás el paso de piezas pequeñas.",
      "title": "Protege el área"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cierra las dos llaves de paso debajo del fregadero girándolas hacia la derecha. Si no existen, cierra la llave general de la vivienda.",
      "title": "Cierra el suministro"
    },
    {
      "text": "Abre el grifo y espera hasta que deje de salir agua. Cierra el grifo cuando las tuberías estén vacías.",
      "title": "Libera la presión"
    },
    {
      "text": "Retira la tapa decorativa de la manija haciendo palanca suavemente con un destornillador plano. Verás el tornillo que sujeta la manija.",
      "title": "Quita la tapa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Afloja el tornillo de la manija con el destornillador adecuado. El tornillo debe quedar suelto sin dañar la cabeza.",
      "title": "Afloja el tornillo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Levanta la manija para retirarla del cuerpo del grifo. Si está atorada, muévela suavemente de lado a lado; no la fuerces.",
      "title": "Retira la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Afloja y retira la tuerca o el aro que sujeta el cartucho, vástago o válvula. Usa una llave ajustable y protege el acabado con un paño.",
      "title": "Retira la sujeción"
    },
    {
      "text": "Extrae el cartucho o vástago en línea recta con unas pinzas. Coloca las piezas sobre el paño y observa su orientación.",
      "title": "Extrae la pieza interna"
    },
    {
      "text": "Inspecciona la arandela, los sellos y el cartucho buscando grietas, desgaste o depósitos minerales. La pieza dañada debe mostrar una deformación o corte visible.",
      "title": "Inspecciona el desgaste"
    },
    {
      "text": "Compra una pieza de reemplazo con la misma forma y medidas que la dañada. Lleva la pieza vieja a la ferretería para comparar el modelo.",
      "title": "Consigue el repuesto"
    },
    {
      "text": "Instala la arandela, el sello o el cartucho nuevo en la misma orientación del anterior. La pieza debe asentarse completamente y quedar nivelada.",
      "title": "Instala el repuesto"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca nuevamente la tuerca o el aro de sujeción y apriétalo con la llave ajustable. Detente cuando quede firme; apretar demasiado puede dañar el grifo.",
      "title": "Sujeta la pieza nueva"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca la manija sobre el vástago o cartucho y alinea su posición con el cuerpo del grifo. Debe moverse sin rozar.",
      "title": "Vuelve a colocar la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aprieta el tornillo de la manija y coloca la tapa decorativa. La manija debe quedar fija y la tapa completamente asentada.",
      "title": "Asegura la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Abre lentamente las llaves de paso girándolas hacia la izquierda. Revisa debajo del fregadero mientras el agua vuelve a circular.",
      "title": "Restablece el agua"
    },
    {
      "text": "Abre y cierra el grifo varias veces y observa la boquilla durante un minuto. La reparación está lista cuando no gotea con el grifo cerrado y no hay fugas debajo del fregadero.",
      "title": "Comprueba la reparación"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Press `Ctrl+S` on Windows or `Cmd+S` on Mac. If the document was already saved, it saves immediately and the unsaved-change indicator disappears.",
      "title": "Save the Document"
    },
    {
      "text": "Select a folder in the Save dialog if it appears. Choose the location where you want to keep the document; the selected folder name should be visible.",
      "title": "Choose a Location"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the **File name** field and type a name for the document. The name should appear in the field without changing the file extension.",
      "title": "Name the Document"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Save**. If a confirmation or replace prompt appears, follow it to finish saving; the dialog should close when complete.",
      "title": "Confirm the Save"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check the document title or tab for the saved filename and make sure no asterisk or unsaved indicator appears. This confirms your work is preserved.",
      "title": "Verify the Document Is Saved"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Clear a large, clean workspace and gather the case, motherboard, CPU, CPU cooler, RAM, storage drive, GPU, power supply, screws, and screwdriver. Keep components in their anti-static bags until needed.",
      "title": "Prepare Your Workspace"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the motherboard on its cardboard box or an anti-static surface. Confirm the CPU socket, RAM slots, storage connectors, and motherboard power connectors are visible.",
      "title": "Position the Motherboard"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lift the CPU socket retention arm and open the socket cover. The socket will be ready for the processor when the cover stays raised.",
      "title": "Open the CPU Socket"
    },
    {
      "text": "Align the CPU’s marked corner with the matching mark on the socket, then lower the CPU straight into place. It should sit flat without pressure; never force it.",
      "title": "Install the CPU"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lower the socket cover and secure the retention arm. The cover may detach as the arm locks; this is normal, and the CPU should remain firmly seated.",
      "title": "Secure the CPU"
    },
    {
      "text": "Attach the CPU cooler above the processor using its included bracket or screws. Tighten each screw gradually in a cross pattern until the cooler is secure.",
      "title": "Mount the CPU Cooler"
    },
    {
      "text": "Connect the cooler’s fan cable to the motherboard header labeled `CPU_FAN`. The connector should fit fully, with no loose pins visible.",
      "title": "Connect the CPU Fan"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open the latches on the selected RAM slots. Align each RAM module’s notch with its slot, then press straight down until both latches click closed.",
      "title": "Install the RAM"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the installed RAM modules gently to confirm they are fully locked. Each module should sit evenly, with both slot latches closed.",
      "title": "Check the RAM"
    },
    {
      "text": "Install the storage drive in its matching connector. For an M.2 drive, insert it at an angle and secure it with its screw; for a SATA drive, mount it in a drive tray.",
      "title": "Install the Storage Drive"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the motherboard into the case and align its mounting holes with the standoffs. The rear ports should fit through the case’s I/O opening.",
      "title": "Place the Motherboard"
    },
    {
      "text": "Secure the motherboard with the included screws. Tighten them until snug, but do not overtighten or bend the board.",
      "title": "Secure the Motherboard"
    },
    {
      "text": "Install the power supply in the case with its fan facing the case’s ventilation opening. Secure it using the four included power-supply screws.",
      "title": "Install the Power Supply"
    },
